Prerequisites
•	Node.js v18 or higher
•	A Salesforce org with CPQ (Steelbrick) installed
•	An Anthropic API account with credits
•	Google Chrome

________________________________________
Local Setup
1. Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/cpq-agent-backend.git
cd cpq-agent-backend
2. Install dependencies
npm install
3. Create the environment file
Create a .env file in the backend folder:
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-your-key-here
PORT=3000
ALLOWED_ORIGIN=chrome-extension://your-extension-id-here
You will get the extension ID in step 5. Leave it as a placeholder for now.

4. Start the backend
node index.js
You should see:
Backend running on port 3000

5. Load the Chrome extension
•	Open Chrome and go to chrome://extensions
•	Enable Developer mode (top right toggle)
•	Click Load unpacked
•	Select the /extension folder
•	Copy the extension ID shown on the card
•	
Update ALLOWED_ORIGIN in your .env with the real extension ID:
ALLOWED_ORIGIN=chrome-extension://abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz123456
Restart the backend after updating.

6. Test it
•	Navigate to a CPQ Quote record in Salesforce
•	Click the CPQ Agent icon in Chrome toolbar
•	The sidebar appears within a few seconds

________________________________________
Deployment (Railway)
The backend can be deployed to Railway for 24/7 availability without running it on your local machine.
1.	Push the backend code to a private GitHub repository
2.	Connect the repository to railway.app
3.	Add environment variables in Railway's Variables tab: 
o	ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
o	PORT = 3000
o	ALLOWED_ORIGIN = your extension's chrome-extension:// origin
4.	Generate a domain in Railway's Settings tab
5.	Update the analyze() function in extension/content.js to point to your Railway URL instead of localhost:3000
6.	Reload the extension in Chrome
Any future changes to the backend are deployed automatically on git push.

________________________________________
Security Notes
•	The Anthropic API key never leaves the backend server
•	The backend uses CORS to reject requests from any origin other than your Chrome extension and Salesforce domains
•	The rep's Salesforce session token is used only to query the REST API and is never forwarded to the backend or stored anywhere
•	The .env file is excluded from version control via .gitignore
•	Rotate your API key immediately if it is ever committed to Git accidentally

